	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="2832457283" id="dsq-comment-2832457283">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="http://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-2832457283">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2016-08-11</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2832457283" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2832457283" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hey Richard!</p><p>Ah, that makes more sense :). Or, more specifically - you mean @Security("ROLE_ADMIN").</p><p>It's more or less perfectly equivalent. The ^/admin in the firewall causes some code to run that compares the URL and if matches, checks for ROLE_ADMIN. If you use @Security, it does the same thing - except instead of checking if the URL matches, it checks to see if that controller class is being executed on this request.</p><p>So it comes down to a matter or preference: do you like protecting by URL better? Or do you like to secure specific controller classes. It's nice to have both options :).</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
